Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: No use or possession of alcohol. No frequenting establishments who's primary purpose is to serve or sell alcohol. No operation of a motor vehicle unless Defendant has valid permit or license.

1:48 PM Defendant James Richard Holm appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Ryan Anthony Reid appeared by video for James Richard Holm.  Prosecuting attorney Allison E. Cogbill in court for the State of Wisconsin. Court calls cases 22CF346, 22TR2796, 2797, and 2798. Defendant's address confirmed. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, enters pleas of not guilty to the misdemeanor count(s), and requests a preliminary hearing. State asks for $2500 cash. No use or possession of alcohol. No frequenting establishments who's primary purpose is to serve or sell alcohol. No operation of a motor vehicle unless Defendant has valid permit or license. State does not see any FTAs but notes the allegations and evading of law enforcement. Attorney Reid asks for $250-$500 cash bond. Defendant is a local resident and is a lifelong resident of Douglas County with family and children in the area. Notes prior convictions but no FTAs. 
Court orders $1000 cash bail. No use or possession of alcohol. No frequenting establishments who's primary purpose is to serve or sell alcohol. No operation of a motor vehicle unless Defendant has valid permit or license. 
State notes trailing traffic matters. Attorney Reid notes that defendant will be entering not guilty plea to traffic tickets. Tickets to trail to status conference.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for September 14, 2022 at 08:45 am.
